Alright, during the day I have already hung up the new nesting box. This is what it looks like in the garden.
However, let's take a look back at it for a moment. “What's inside it?” seems like no one has asked about it.
The top part is an ESP32 camera board with a fisheye camera lens and a red infrared LED light taken from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The plastic box shape is unusual, because the nest box side panel can rotate. I bought it like this, and it can't be modified, so I had to design it according to this situation.
Because there is no power supply in the garden, the entire device is powered by a solar panel and a 2600mAh 18650 lithium battery.
I haven't taken a photo of the battery or charger, but this is a photo of the solar panel.
The gray box on the side of the nest box contains the battery.
The device can run for approximately 4 hours after being fully charged.
I call this a "special feature". In this way, the birds can have some private space too.
Initially, I was not sure if the network in the garden was good enough to support this setup. The old access points I replaced last autumn would definitely not work.
However, the coverage of the new access points was completely fine.
